<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-700-030  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 700 030.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC User  August 30 1989 n114 p60(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT EMAP Business and Computer Publications1989.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>TexAtrix. (Software Review) (utility package for ASCII text files)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Dorner, Jane.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   Scarabeus Software (distribution).andO;Product:   TexAtrix (Computer program) (evaluation).andO;Topic:     EvaluationUtility ProgramsASCIIReadability Analysis.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>TexAtrix is very easy to use.andP;  It doesn't cost much, but it doesn't do mucheither.andP;  It gives a quick readability assessment of any ASCII text file,counting the words, characters, number of sentences and paragraphs,proportion of long words (ten letters or more), average words per sentenceand the Fog Index.andP;  All this is of limited use, espe- cially for users whodon't know what the Fog index is and won't be helped by thedocumentation-on-disk that comes with the program.andM;According to the program, the Fog Index gives a figure which represents theapproximate years of education required to read a particular document withease - for example, 7-8 for The Sun and 15 for The Daily Telegraph.andP;  Userswho get a score above 17 years should be aware that the ordinary person willfind the writing dense and obscure.andM;The advice offeredis 'simplest is often best'.andP;  All very laudable, but howuseful is a program which can't supply a little more information on whatcould be changed to improve readability?andM;Moreover, far more reliable sources give quite different readability scoresfor our national Press.andM;The Fog Index is more usefully calculated in terms of reading age and figuressupplied by the Society of Authors ie.andP;  12.6 for The Mirror; 12.7 for TheSun; 13.2 for The Express; 16.2 for The Times; 16.6 for The Telegraph and16.9 for The Guardian.andM;If you want to attract the public, go for a reading age of 13 (a score of9-10 on TexAtrix).andM;TexAtrix works out  score with the formula: average words per sentence, pluslong words, and multiplied by 0.4.andP;  it's easy to see that better scores canbe achieved by reducing the number of words per sentence or long words.andO;That's good practice - as far as it goes.andM;If there are any writers who can use TexAtrix to improve their writingskills, then good luck to them.andO;</TEXT></DOC>